"""
MKT Context Commentary — Nehemiah chapters 11–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-nehemiah-11-12.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/nehemiah.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/nehemiah.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/nehemiah.json (prior chapters for style/terminology)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch11: population of Jerusalem by lot-casting; parallels 1 Chr 9:2-21
- Ch12: dedicatory ceremony (ḥanukkat haḥômāh) is the narrative climax of Nehemiah 1-12
- 'Holy city' (ʿîr haqqōḏeš) designation noted at 11:1, 11:18 — a rare term in the HB
- 'Book of the Chronicles' in 12:23 is a temple/court archive, not the canonical books
- 'Days of Darius the Persian' in 12:22 is ambiguous: Darius II (423-404) or III (336-330)
- Two processions in ch12 go in opposite directions and converge at the temple
- Joy 'heard far away' in 12:43 deliberately echoes Ezra 3:13
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEH1112 = {
    "11": {
        "1": "<p>The casting of lots (<em>gôrāl</em>, H1486) to determine who resettles Jerusalem echoes the land-allotment system established under Joshua (Josh 18–19), where the same device assigned tribal territories. The application of this specifically Israelite judicial practice to a Persian-period population distribution problem signals that Nehemiah understands the community's settlement as a continuation of the conquest-era covenant land occupation. The designation <strong>'the holy city'</strong> (<em>ʿîr haqqōḏeš</em>) is rare — used only at Neh 11:1, 11:18, Isa 48:2, and Isa 52:1 in the Hebrew Bible — and signals that Jerusalem's holiness derives not from its walls but from YHWH's dwelling presence within it.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Those who <strong>willingly offered</strong> (<em>hiṯnaddeḇ</em>, H5068) to live in Jerusalem receive the community's blessing. The same term appears at Ezra 1:6, 2:68, and 3:5 for freewill offerings to the temple fund, and in 1 Chr 29:5–17 for the great freewill offering for the temple treasury under David. The verb belongs to a specifically Israelite vocabulary of voluntary covenant generosity — distinct from tithing or tax obligation — and Nehemiah frames voluntary urban resettlement as an act of religious devotion rather than civic compliance.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The list is introduced with the standard formula 'heads of the province' (<em>rāʾšê hamməḏînāh</em>), placing the community explicitly in the Persian provincial administration as <em>Yəhûḏ</em> (the name of the province, attested on Persian-period bullae and coins). The compound settler categories — Israelites, priests, Levites, temple servants (<em>nəṯînîm</em>), and descendants of Solomon's servants — directly parallel the returnee list in Ezra 2//Neh 7. The closest structural parallel to this settlement register is 1 Chr 9:2–21, which gives an equivalent roster but framed as the pre-exilic population returning to their ancestral towns after the exile.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The Judahite genealogies trace descent through the <strong>Perez line</strong> (<em>bənê-Pereṣ</em>) — the dominant branch of Judah through which the Davidic line ran (Ruth 4:18–22; 1 Chr 2:4–15). Listing Perez descendants first among Jerusalem's resettled inhabitants implicitly maintains the Davidic connection to the city even in the absence of a ruling Davidic king. The genealogical depth (five or six generations) is typical of Persian-period lists, which anchor identity claims in documented lineage rather than political power.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The Shilonite line (<em>haššilōnî</em>) refers to descendants of Shelah, the third son of Judah (1 Chr 9:5; contrast v4's Perez line). The deep genealogy through Col-hozeh, Hazaiah, and Adaiah serves the Persian administrative function of establishing land and temple-duty claims. Col-hozeh ('all-seer') appears again in Neh 3:15 as the father of Shallum who repaired the Fountain Gate — the repetition of distinctive names across different chapters is a marker of the authentic archival character of Nehemiah's memoirs.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The census total of <strong>468 capable men</strong> (<em>anšê ḥāyil</em>) from the Perez line gives demographic texture to what would otherwise be an abstract list. The total population of Persian-period Jerusalem has been estimated archaeologically at 500–1,500 residents — 468 adult males from one clan alone would be a significant concentration. The term <em>anšê ḥāyil</em> (capable/valiant men) echoes the military census language of Numbers and suggests the list derives from a Persian administrative register that tracked able-bodied residents.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The Benjaminite settlers are listed second, consistent with the post-exilic pattern throughout Ezra-Nehemiah where Judah and Benjamin together constitute the core restoration community. Sallu son of Meshullam's genealogy runs seven generations deep — a typical claim for the founding of a <em>bêt-āḇ</em> (ancestral house), the basic Persian-period administrative unit. Benjamin's presence in Jerusalem alongside Judah maintains the two-tribe identity of the restoration community (1 Kgs 12:21–23), distinguishing it from the ten lost tribes of the north.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Gabbai and Sallai are mentioned without genealogies, likely representing sub-groups that joined Sallu's household association rather than independent lineage-holders. The total of <strong>928</strong> Benjaminite men is substantially larger than the Perez count (468), consistent with Benjamin's traditionally strong urban presence — Jerusalem had historically been on the Judah-Benjamin border (Josh 18:28; Josh 15:8), and Benjaminites had significant ancestral claims to sections of the city.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The administrative structure — an <em>pāqîḏ</em> (overseer/commissioner) over the tribe and a <em>mišneh</em> (second-in-command) over the city — mirrors Persian provincial administrative vocabulary. Joel son of Zichri as overseer and Judah son of Senuah as second-in-command over the city (not the tribe) suggests a differentiated governance structure: tribal hierarchy and civic administration ran in parallel. The title <em>mišneh</em> ('second') appears in the Jerusalem context also at 2 Kgs 22:14 (Huldah the prophetess lived in the Mishneh district).</p>",
        "10": "<p>The priestly families begin with Jedaiah son of Joiarib — the line later prominent in the Maccabean period, as the Hasmoneans were of the Joiarib course (1 Macc 2:1). This lineage appears in the original returnee list (Ezra 2:36; Neh 7:39) and is one of the four leading priestly courses. Jachin is listed without genealogy, suggesting he may represent the priestly course as a whole (the 21st course, 1 Chr 24:17) rather than an individual genealogical head.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Seraiah's identification as <strong>'the chief officer of the house of God'</strong> (<em>nāgîḏ bêt-hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) places him at the apex of the temple administrative hierarchy. The title <em>nāgîḏ</em> (prince/officer) is used for the chief temple administrator and for the Davidic king — the overlap is intentional: in the absence of a Davidic king, the temple chief officer carries related dignitary status. The Zadokite lineage (through Ahitub and Meraioth) was the legitimating ancestry for the high priestly line in Second Temple Judaism.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The figure of <strong>822</strong> priestly relatives performing temple service represents the core professional clergy of Jerusalem. The Persian-period temple required ongoing personnel for daily sacrifices, Sabbath observances, new moon festivals, and the annual pilgrimage calendar — a staff of 822 is not excessive for this liturgical load. The second family group, Adaiah and his 242 ancestral heads, likely represents a second priestly course rotation resident in the city year-round.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The 242 <strong>heads of ancestral houses</strong> (<em>rāʾšê ʾāḇôṯ</em>) in Adaiah's line form the middle-rank priestly leadership. The distinction between 'heads of ancestral houses' (administrative leaders) and 'men of valor' (v14, military-capable) reflects the dual civic-military role that the clergy maintained in the fortified post-exilic city. Amashai son of Azarel represents yet a third priestly sub-group from the Immer course — one of the four original returnee priestly courses from Ezra 2:37.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The description of priestly relatives as <strong>'men of valor'</strong> (<em>gibbôrê ḥāyil</em>, H2428) — the same term used for elite warriors (Judg 6:12; 1 Sam 9:1) — reveals that in the post-exilic city, the priestly community also performed military-civic functions. The wall-building narrative (Neh 3–4) already showed priests working with weapons; this classification formalizes that dual role. The 'great one' (<em>haggəḏôlîm</em>) may be a title meaning 'great man' or a proper name Haggedolim.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The Levitical families begin with Shemaiah, whose genealogy runs through Hashabiah — a name appearing frequently in Nehemiah's Levite lists (Neh 3:17; 10:11; 12:24). The Levites were not allotted territory in Israel's original land distribution (Num 18:20) but were distributed across Levitical cities; the concentration of 284 Levites in Jerusalem (v18) represents a deliberate post-exilic policy of centering the temple-service personnel rather than dispersing them.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Shabbethai and Jozabad are identified as leaders over the <strong>'external affairs of the house of God'</strong> (<em>hammělāʾḵāh haḥîṣônāh lĕḇêṯ-hāʾĕlōhîm</em>). This administrative term distinguishes the external logistics and civic functions of the temple from the internal ritual and liturgical roles. Jozabad appears in Ezra 8:33 (assisting in the weighing of the silver and gold) and Ezra 10:23 (among those with foreign wives) — the same administrative functionary operating across multiple Ezra-Nehemiah crises.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Mattaniah son of Micha from the Asaph line is identified as the one who 'led the thanksgiving in prayer' (<em>rōʾš hayyôḏāh lihillāh</em>) — a liturgical leadership role. The Asaph lineage was the premier musical guild in the Second Temple period (Ezra 2:41; 3:10), traced back to Asaph, David's chief musician (1 Chr 25:1–9). Bakbukiah as 'second' continues the administrative pairing structure noted at v9. The entire Levitical musical ministry in Jerusalem traced its authority to the Davidic-era cult establishment.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The total of <strong>284 Levites</strong> in the holy city is notably smaller than the priestly count (822 + 242 + 128 = 1,192). This numerical disproportion is historically attested: the Levites were consistently under-represented in the return community — Ezra 8:15 notes that no Levites at all initially came forward for the second return, requiring a special recruitment mission. The imbalance reflects both the reduced prestige of the Levitical role under the post-exilic priestly hierarchy and the Levites' traditional dispersal across the land.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The <strong>gatekeepers</strong> (<em>šôʿărîm</em>) numbered 172 — a professional guild responsible for the security of the temple complex. Their role was not merely custodial: in the Persian-period temple, gatekeepers controlled access to the sacred precincts, managed the treasury storerooms, and maintained purity protocols at the threshold between the sacred and common. They are consistently listed as a distinct category in every return community census (Ezra 2:42; Neh 7:45), indicating the importance of this role for the ongoing function of the temple.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The note that 'the rest of Israel — the priests and Levites not settled in Jerusalem — lived in all the other towns of Judah, each in his ancestral property' (<em>naḥălāṯô</em>) anchors the provincial settlement in the ancestral land-tenure system. The term <em>naḥălāh</em> (inheritance/property) carries the theological weight of the original land grant in the Pentateuch — each family's plot was not merely real estate but a covenant-given portion. The Persian provincial system actually preserved this concept by registering land claims by ancestral lineage rather than by conquest or purchase.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The <strong>Ophel</strong> — the fortified hill immediately south of the Temple Mount — was the traditional residence of temple servants (<em>nəṯînîm</em>). The Ophel's proximity to the temple made it the logical location for the lowest-rank temple functionaries who needed to be present for daily service rotations. The <em>nəṯînîm</em> (H5411, 'those given') were of foreign origin, traditionally traced to the Gibeonites whom Joshua assigned to temple service (Josh 9:27; Ezra 8:20). Ziha and Gispa as their overseers represent the senior administrative figures of this distinct community within the restoration population.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The Levitical overseer Uzzi's identification through five generations to the Asaph line demonstrates how the Asaphite musical guild maintained organizational continuity across the post-exilic period. The note that he oversaw 'the work of the house of God' (<em>mĕlāʾḵāh lĕḇêṯ-hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) uses the same administrative vocabulary as the temple-building narratives in Exodus (the tabernacle work, <em>mĕlāʾḵāh</em>) — a deliberate echo of the original construction and equipping of Israel's sacred space.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The reference to a <strong>royal decree</strong> (<em>miṣwaṯ hammelek</em>) establishing a 'fixed daily portion' (<em>dāḇār-yôm bəyôm</em>) for the singers is a remarkable piece of Persian administrative information. It indicates that the Achaemenid Persian court actively subsidized the Jerusalem temple's musical establishment — consistent with the broader Persian policy of funding local religious institutions (Ezra 6:8–10; 7:20–22). The 'fixed daily portion' mirrors the same term (<em>dəḇar-yôm bəyôm</em>) used for the daily allotment to Jehoiachin at the Babylonian court (2 Kgs 25:30).</p>",
        "24": "<p>Pethahiah son of Meshezabeel, from the Zerah branch of Judah, served as <strong>'the king's liaison'</strong> (<em>ləyaḏ hammelek lĕḵol-dāḇār lāʿām</em>, literally 'at the king's hand for all matters concerning the people'). This Persian administrative title — essentially a liaison officer (<em>ṣôlēaḥ</em>, commissioner) between the Jewish community and the Achaemenid court — parallels the role of Nehemiah himself as cupbearer/trusted official to the king. The Zerah lineage represents the secondary branch of Judah after Perez; its presence at this level of Persian court access shows that Persian patronage was not restricted to the Davidic/Perez line.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The village settlement list (vv25–36) covers the geographical extent of the Persian province of <em>Yəhûḏ</em>. Kiriath-arba is the ancient name for Hebron (Gen 23:2; Josh 14:15), the city of the patriarchal burial ground and David's first capital — its resettlement by post-exilic Judahites signals the recovery of the ancestral heartland. Dibon lay east of Judah (originally Moabite territory, Num 32:3) and Jekabzeel in the Negev — the community was resettling not just the urban core but the peripheral regions of the traditional Davidic kingdom.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Jeshua (not the post-exilic high priest, but a town, modern Tell es-Sawâ), Moladah, and Beth-pelet are all in the northern Negev, identified in earlier tribal allotment lists (Josh 15:26–28; 19:2–3). The recovery of these southern settlements is historically significant: the Negev towns had been abandoned or occupied by Edomites (later called Idumeans) during and after the Babylonian period. Resettlement here represents a territorial claim against Edomite encroachment — a tension that underlies the book of Obadiah and the later Maccabean-era conflicts with Idumea.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Hazar-shual ('fox settlement') and Beersheba are in the southernmost extent of traditional Israelite territory — 'from Dan to Beersheba' was the proverbial border formula for the full extent of the land (Judg 20:1; 1 Sam 3:20). Resettling Beersheba is symbolically charged: it was Abraham's covenant location with Abimelech (Gen 21:33), Isaac's altar site (Gen 26:23–25), and the southern anchor of Jacob's journeys (Gen 28:10). The post-exilic resettlement of Beersheba implicitly reclaims the full patriarchal land promise.</p>",
        "28": "<p>Ziklag was the town given to David by the Philistine king Achish during his time as an outlaw (1 Sam 27:6), later belonging permanently to the kings of Judah. Its resettlement by post-exilic Judahites reflects the same claim to Davidic-era territory visible throughout the list. Meconah is not elsewhere attested and may be a small settlement that disappeared from the record — the specificity of such minor place names argues for the antiquity and archival character of the list rather than its literary invention.</p>",
        "29": "<p>En-rimmon ('pomegranate spring') and Zorah were both sites in the Shephelah, the foothills between the coastal plain and the Judean highlands. Zorah is especially notable as the hometown of Samson (Judg 13:2, 25; 16:31) — its resettlement in the post-exilic period represents recovery of the western territories that had been under Philistine and then later Idumean influence during the exile period. The Shephelah was economically productive for olive oil and grain, making its resettlement economically as well as symbolically significant.</p>",
        "30": "<p>Zanoah, Adullam, Lachish, and Azekah represent the outer perimeter of the Shephelah zone. Lachish was the second most important city in Judah (after Jerusalem) and the last to fall to the Babylonians before Jerusalem (Jer 34:7; the Lachish letters document its final days). Azekah is mentioned alongside Lachish in that same Jeremiah passage. The resettlement boundary 'from Beersheba to the Valley of Hinnom' marks the southern and northern limits of the province: Hinnom is the ravine immediately south and west of Jerusalem, and Beersheba anchors the far south.</p>",
        "31": "<p>The Benjaminite settlement list begins at Geba, a key northern border town, and runs through Michmash (famous for Jonathan's exploit against the Philistines, 1 Sam 14:1–14), Aija (likely biblical Ai, Gen 12:8), and Bethel. Bethel was a contested religious site: it had been a major altar center under Jeroboam (1 Kgs 12:28–29) and had been destroyed by Josiah (2 Kgs 23:15). Its reoccupation by Benjaminites in the post-exilic period suggests the northern Benjaminite borderlands were being gradually repopulated, though the site's altar history would have remained theologically sensitive.</p>",
        "32": "<p>Anathoth — the hometown of Jeremiah (Jer 1:1) and a Levitical city originally assigned to the Kohathites (Josh 21:18) — appears in the Benjaminite settlement list. Jeremiah's famous field purchase in Anathoth (Jer 32:6–15) was an act of prophetic hope in the midst of the Babylonian siege: the field would one day be worth buying again. The post-exilic resettlement of Anathoth represents the historical realization of that prophetic hope — the land is indeed being reoccupied. Nob was the priestly city famously destroyed by Saul (1 Sam 22:19); its resettlement also signals recovery of traumatic pre-exilic losses.</p>",
        "33": "<p>Hazor (not the northern Hazor of Josh 11:10, but a Benjaminite settlement, also at Neh 3:2 as 'the men of Jericho'), Ramah, and Gittaim are in the central Benjaminite territory, north of Jerusalem. Ramah is where Rachel's tomb tradition placed her weeping for her children (Jer 31:15 — the text Matthew applies to the massacre of the innocents, Matt 2:18). The concentration of Benjaminite settlements in this zone reflects the fact that Benjamin's tribal territory essentially surrounded the northern approaches to Jerusalem, making Benjaminite urban presence critical for the city's security.</p>",
        "34": "<p>Hadid, Zeboim, and Neballat are towns in the western approaches to Jerusalem, in the territory between the Shephelah and the central ridge. Hadid appears in the returnee list of Ezra 2:33//Neh 7:37 as the origin of 725 returned exiles. The cluster of towns suggests a relatively dense post-exilic resettlement of the western Benjaminite zone — a security priority given that the major threat to Jerusalem historically came from western powers approaching through the Aijalon valley corridor.</p>",
        "35": "<p>Lod (modern Lydda, later Ludd, today near Ben Gurion airport) and Ono are the two major towns of the western coastal-plain edge — significantly further west and lower in elevation than the central Benjaminite ridge towns. These settlements are in the traditional territory of Ephraim, not Benjamin — their assignment to Benjaminite settlement reflects the post-exilic compression of all the remaining Israelite population into the two surviving tribes. The <strong>'Valley of Craftsmen'</strong> (<em>gêʾ hāḥārāšîm</em>) is named for its skilled-trade inhabitants, and its appearance here and in 1 Chr 4:14 suggests it was a known artisan district in the western Shephelah.</p>",
        "36": "<p>The final notice — that 'some of the Levitical divisions from Judah were assigned to Benjamin' — documents a pragmatic redistribution of the Levitical service personnel across the tribal territories. With the Levitical cities of both Judah and Benjamin to staff (Josh 21:4–8), and with the community smaller than its pre-exilic predecessor, the practical pooling of Levitical manpower across tribal assignments reflects the Persian-period reality: the restoration community was rebuilding its institutional structures with a fraction of the pre-exilic population.</p>"
    },
    "12": {
        "1": "<p>The list of priests and Levites who 'went up' (<em>hāʿōlîm</em>) with Zerubbabel and Jeshua locates this roster at the first return from Babylon (ca. 538 BCE, Ezra 1–2). Zerubbabel as Davidic governor and Jeshua (Joshua) as high priest formed the dual leadership of the first return — a pattern that Haggai and Zechariah interpret as a messianic two-anointed-ones structure (Zech 4:11–14; 6:9–15). This list thus anchors the priestly establishment of Nehemiah's day to the founding moment of the restoration, establishing continuity over roughly a century of post-exilic history.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The names Amariah, Malluch, and Hattush appear in the returnee lists (Ezra 2; Neh 7) and in the covenant signatories list (Neh 10). Hattush appears in Ezra 8:2 as a Davidic descendant who returned with Ezra — the overlap of names across priestly and Davidic genealogies in these lists is not confusion but evidence of how the post-exilic community constituted itself: by careful cross-referencing of lineage claims with administrative records.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Shechaniah appears in both Ezra 10:2 (the first to confess the mixed-marriage crisis) and Neh 3:29 (the 'keeper of the East Gate'), while Rehum is a signatory of the opposition letter in Ezra 4:8–16. The reuse of these names across different narrative contexts raises the question of whether the same individuals appear in multiple roles or whether these are common family names. Persian-period prosopography (the study of named individuals in administrative texts) suggests both: some names recur within the same family through generations.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Iddo, Ginnetho (or Ginnethoi, v16), and Abijah appear in the priestly course lists. Abijah is the eighth priestly course in the Davidic reorganization (1 Chr 24:10) — this is the course of Zechariah, father of John the Baptist (Luke 1:5). The continuity from the first return under Zerubbabel through to the New Testament priesthood is documented in exactly this kind of genealogical list: Luke's identification of Zechariah's course allows a reader of both Testaments to trace the priestly lineage from the post-exilic foundation all the way to the birth of the Messiah's forerunner.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Miamin, Maadiah, and Bilgah continue the list of priestly houses from Zerubbabel's return. Bilgah appears as a priestly course name in 1 Chr 24:14 (the fifteenth course). These names are not merely archival — they represent the ongoing priestly families who maintained the sacrificial calendar of the second temple for the five centuries between Zerubbabel and the destruction of the temple in 70 CE. The New Testament world's priestly establishment is the direct institutional descendant of this post-exilic reorganization.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Shemaiah and Joiarib complete the initial list. Joiarib ('YHWH contends') is the priestly course from which the Hasmoneans descended — 1 Macc 2:1 identifies Mattathias as 'son of John, son of Simeon, a priest of the sons of Joiarib.' The Maccabean revolt's leadership thus came from this first-return priestly family, and the Maccabean-era Hanukkah celebration shares its root with the wall dedication in this chapter (<em>ḥanukkāh</em>). The long institutional memory of these priestly families connected Nehemiah's wall to the Maccabean temple rededication.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The summary formula 'these were the leading priests and their associates in the days of Jeshua' (<em>bîmê yēšûaʿ</em>) anchors the list temporally. The high priest Jeshua is the same figure restored in Zechariah's vision (Zech 3:1–5; 6:11) where he receives a crown and a messianic promise. The phrase 'in the days of Jeshua' begins a series of temporal anchors (vv7, 12, 22, 26) that organize the genealogical material around the successive high priests — using the high priestly succession as a chronological framework in the absence of a Davidic king.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The Levitical leaders Jeshua, Binnui, Kadmiel, Sherebiah, Judah, and Mattaniah formed the core musical and administrative Levitical establishment of the first return. Sherebiah appears in Ezra 8:18, 24 as the outstanding Levite recruited for the second return — 'a man of insight' — and in Neh 9:4–5 as a liturgical leader at the great assembly. The consistency of these names across the Ezra-Nehemiah narrative reflects either long-lived individuals or more likely the use of family titles (a family known by its founding ancestor's name).</p>",
        "9": "<p>The detail that Bakbukiah and Unni 'stood <em>opposite</em> them (<em>lĕneḡdām</em>) during the service watches' reflects the antiphonal worship structure of the second temple. The Levitical choirs were organized into two groups that responded to one another — a musical form attested in the Psalms (Ps 136 with its refrain; Ps 118:1–4 with ascending responses) and described in the Chronicles as the Davidic pattern (1 Chr 25:8). This antiphonal structure survives in the Christian liturgical tradition of chanting the Psalms in two choirs (e.g., Anglican choral evensong).</p>",
        "10": "<p>The high priestly succession from Jeshua to Eliashib runs: Jeshua (first return, ca. 538 BCE) → Joiakim (fl. ca. 500–480) → Eliashib (fl. ca. 450–433, contemporary of Nehemiah). This succession spans roughly a century. Eliashib is the high priest who gave Tobiah the storeroom in the temple (Neh 13:4–7) — his family's alliance with Tobiah the Ammonite and Sanballat the Horonite (whose daughter Joiada's son married, Neh 13:28) reveals that the high priestly family was deeply entangled in the regional political networks that Nehemiah opposed.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Joiada → Jonathan → Jaddua extends the high priestly succession into the late fifth or early fourth century. Jaddua is the most historically intriguing figure: Josephus (<em>Antiquities</em> 11.7–8) places Jaddua at the time of Alexander the Great's conquest (334–323 BCE), claiming Alexander met the high priest at Jerusalem and honored the temple. Whether historical or legendary, this places Jaddua at the transition from Persian to Hellenistic period — making the succession documented here span from the Persian founding (538 BCE) to the Hellenistic era, roughly 200 years of continuous institutional memory.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The 'days of Joiakim' (<em>bîmê yôyāqîm</em>) provide the temporal anchor for the heads of the priestly families listed in vv12–21. Each entry follows the formula 'from X's line, Y' — organizing the priestly houses by their founding ancestor from the first return (vv1–7) and their current head under Joiakim (ca. 500–480 BCE). This cross-generational record-keeping is characteristic of Persian administrative practice, which required continuous genealogical documentation for temple-service eligibility.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Meshullam of Ezra's line and Jehohanan of Amariah's line represent prominent families — Meshullam appears as a common name throughout Ezra-Nehemiah (at least nine different Meshullams are mentioned). The Persian-period practice of using the same prestigious names across generations within a family creates the naming complexity that makes these lists difficult to track. The repetition is not scribal error but a deliberate family strategy: bearing an ancestor's prestigious name was a claim to ancestral honor and temple-service rights.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Jonathan of Malluch's line and Joseph of Shebaniah's line continue the register. The name Jonathan ('YHWH has given') was common in the priestly community and appears in Ezra 8:6, 10:15, and Neh 12:35 — multiple distinct individuals. The deliberate preservation of these family-by-family priestly records reflects the careful genealogical consciousness of the restoration community, which understood its institutional legitimacy as dependent on unbroken priestly lineage (Neh 7:64–65 records that some genealogically uncertain priests were excluded from eating the most holy things until a priest could decide the matter with Urim and Thummim).</p>",
        "15": "<p>Adna of Harim's line and Helkai of Meraioth's line represent the fourth and fifth priestly courses in the Davidic organization. The Harim course (1 Chr 24:8) produced 1,017 returnees in the first aliyah (Ezra 2:39) — one of the larger priestly family groups. The internal organization of the priestly community by course (Heb. <em>mišmārot</em>) was a Persian-period adaptation of the Davidic/Solomonic 24-course rotation (1 Chr 24:1–19) to the post-exilic temple's reduced scale and personnel.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Zechariah of Iddo's line is likely the prophet Zechariah (Zech 1:1, 7 — 'Zechariah son of Berechiah son of Iddo') whose visions of Joshua the high priest and the messianic Branch (Zech 3–4; 6:9–15) are among the most explicitly Christ-anticipating prophetic texts in the OT. The prophet was thus himself a priestly family head — preaching from within the temple establishment rather than from prophetic outsider status. This list documents the institutional home of one of scripture's most theologically rich post-exilic voices.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The note that Moadiah and Miniamin share a line entry ('from Miniamin's and Moadiah's lines, Piltai') may reflect a family merger or variant naming convention — Persian-period family records sometimes consolidated smaller houses under a joint heading when one lacked sufficient membership to maintain an independent roster. The Abijah course (Zichri as head) is the course of Zechariah father of John the Baptist (Luke 1:5), making this entry the institutional location of John the Baptist's priestly family in the second temple's organizational history.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The Bilgah course (Shammua as head) and Shemaiah course (Jehonathan) continue the register. 'Shammua' and 'Jehonathan' are both archaic Hebrew names with long biblical histories — Shammua was one of the twelve spies (Num 13:4) and a son of David (2 Sam 5:14). The persistence of these patriarchal names across the post-exilic period reflects the community's deliberate use of naming to anchor itself in the full sweep of Israelite history — from the wilderness to the return.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Mattenai of Joiarib's line and Uzzi of Jedaiah's line continue the register. By this point in the list (the 19th and 20th priestly course-families), the reader has been walked through the organizational structure of the temple's clerical establishment at the beginning of the fifth century. The cumulative effect is documentary: what might seem like dry genealogy is the institutional backbone of a community reconstituting itself around its most important institution, the temple, in a hostile post-exilic environment.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Kallai of Sallai's line and Eber of Amok's line round out the mid-list priestly families. Amok ('deep, inscrutable') is an unusual name appearing only here and in the original returnee list (Neh 7:44 variant). The name's rarity argues for the antiquity of the source: invented genealogical lists tend toward common, prestigious names rather than obscure ones. The documentary quality of these lists is similar to the Elephantine papyri — Persian-period administrative records from the Jewish colony in Egypt that show the same kind of careful personal-name preservation.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Hashabiah of Hilkiah's line and Nethanel of Jedaiah's line complete the priestly-course register for the days of Joiakim. The list covers 22 priestly families (vv12–21), somewhat fewer than the 24 Davidic courses (1 Chr 24), suggesting either that not all courses were represented in the post-exilic community or that two courses had merged. The incompleteness is itself historically informative: it shows the real contraction of the priestly establishment through the exile, not an artificially complete 24-course roster.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The Levitical registration 'down to the reign of Darius the Persian' (<em>malkûṯ dārĕyāweš happārsî</em>) is chronologically ambiguous — potentially Darius II (423–404 BCE) or Darius III (336–330 BCE). The latter would push Jaddua (v11) into the Hellenistic period (Josephus's claim). Most scholars identify 'Darius the Persian' as Darius II, placing Jaddua in the late fifth century. The ambiguity is ancient: the text uses the qualifying 'the Persian' to distinguish him from other Dariuses — suggesting the author was aware there were multiple Persian kings by this name.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The <strong>'Book of the Chronicles'</strong> (<em>sēper diḇrê hayyāmîm</em>) cited as the source for Levitical genealogies is almost certainly a temple or court archive — a Persian-period administrative record — rather than the canonical books of Chronicles (which use the same Hebrew title but are a different literary work). Persian administrative practice required temples to maintain detailed personnel records for tax and benefice purposes; this temple archive is the institutional equivalent of Persian court daybooks. The reference gives Nehemiah's genealogical work a documentary basis beyond the text itself.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The Levitical leaders Hashabiah, Sherebiah, and Jeshua son of Kadmiel led the antiphonal worship 'as David the man of God had commanded, division facing division' (<em>mîdgāh lĕneḡeḏ mîdgāh</em>). The phrase 'man of God' (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) is a prophetic title used for Moses (Deut 33:1), Samuel (1 Sam 9:6), Elijah (1 Kgs 17:18), and Elisha (2 Kgs 4:7). Applying it to David frames his worship institution not as royal preference but as prophetic revelation — the antiphonal pattern was divinely authorized through David's prophetic insight, giving it perpetual normative status.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The gatekeeper roster — Mattaniah, Bakbukiah, Obadiah, Meshullam, Talmon, and Akkub — guarded 'the storerooms beside the gates' (<em>ʾōṣĕrôṯ</em>). The storerooms adjacent to the gates were the primary repositories for tithes, firstfruits, and votive offerings — they required security both from theft and from ritual contamination. Akkub and Talmon appear in the original returnee list as gatekeeper families (Ezra 2:42), showing these gatekeeper guilds maintained their identity across the century from the first return to Nehemiah's governorship.</p>",
        "26": "<p>The historical double-anchor 'in the days of Joiakim… and in the days of Nehemiah the governor and Ezra the priest and scribe' places the preceding genealogical lists within the administrative framework of two distinct periods: the early fifth century (Joiakim's high priesthood) and the mid-fifth century (Nehemiah's governorship, ca. 445–433 BCE). The explicit mention of Ezra as 'the priest and scribe' (<em>hakkōhēn hassōfēr</em>) — combining the two most important institutional roles — signals his foundational importance for the community's self-understanding as a Torah-centered priestly people.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The <strong>dedication of the wall</strong> (<em>ḥanukkat haḥômāh</em>) marks the narrative and theological climax of the entire book. The term <em>ḥanukkāh</em> (H2598, 'dedication, consecration') is the same root as the Maccabean-era rededication of the temple in 164 BCE (1 Macc 4:36–59) — the Hanukkah festival. The post-exilic wall dedication thus stands as a forerunner of the Maccabean dedication: both involved the consecration of a sacred boundary (city wall / temple altar) that had been profaned by Gentile interference, and both were celebrated with extraordinary joy. The gathering of Levites from throughout the province for the ceremony reflects its status as a national religious event, not merely a civic one.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The singers were gathered from 'the area around Jerusalem' (<em>mikkiḵar hayyardēn</em>, literally 'from the Jordan circuit/region') and from the Netophathite villages. The Netophathites were a clan of Levitical musicians settled near Bethlehem (Neh 7:26; 1 Chr 2:54), whose connection to the Asaph and Jeduthun guilds is attested in the superscriptions of 1 Chr 9:16 and Neh 12:35. The geographical gathering of musicians from the surrounding region for the wall dedication mirrors the gathering of Levitical singers for Solomon's temple dedication (2 Chr 5:11–13), invoking that founding moment for the new Jerusalem's celebration.</p>",
        "29": "<p>Beth-gilgal, Geba, and Azmaveth are north and east of Jerusalem. Gilgal was Israel's first encampment in Canaan after crossing the Jordan (Josh 4:19–20) — a site of covenantal circumcision (Josh 5:2–9) and the beginning of the conquest. The singers having 'established their own villages around Jerusalem' (<em>wəkōrmê gittāʾîm ʾāśû ləhem ḥăṣērîm sĕḇîḇôṯ yĕrûšālāim</em>) reflects the institutional reality that the Levitical musicians required residential infrastructure for the ongoing temple service — they were not occasional visitors but permanent professional staff who had organized their own housing communities in the temple's geographic orbit.</p>",
        "30": "<p>The <strong>purification</strong> (<em>yiṭṭahărû</em>, H2891) of priests, Levites, people, gates, and wall follows standard Levitical protocol (Lev 8:15; Num 19; Ezek 43:20–22). Gates and walls could not participate in a sacred event in an unclean state — the extension of purification rites to architectural structures reflects the theology that the entire city of Jerusalem, not merely the temple interior, was sacred space. The city-wide purification before the dedication ceremony mirrors the preparation for the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:10–15) and for the original temple dedication under Solomon (1 Kgs 8:4–5).</p>",
        "31": "<p>Nehemiah's first-person voice returns ('I brought the leaders of Judah up onto the top of the wall') after the genealogical sections (vv1–26). The two <strong>great thanksgiving choirs</strong> (<em>tôḏōṯ gĕḏōlôṯ</em>) proceeding in opposite directions around the wall mirror the two-procession structure of the temple dedication under Solomon (2 Chr 5–7, where the priests processed from the tent of meeting to the new temple). Going to the right (<em>ləmîn hayāmîn</em>) means southward from the Valley Gate, toward the Dung Gate — the route described for the wall repairs in Neh 3:13–14.</p>",
        "32": "<p>Hoshaiah led 'half of the leaders of Judah' (<em>waḥăṣî śārê yĕhûḏāh</em>) in the first procession. The division of the civic leadership between two processions reflects the two-directional design: one half circumambulating the wall clockwise (southward first), the other counterclockwise (northward first). The arrangement echoes the covenant renewal ceremony at Shechem (Josh 8:33) where half Israel stood on Mount Gerizim and half on Mount Ebal — communal acts in Israel regularly split the community into two representative halves for symbolic completeness.</p>",
        "33": "<p>Azariah, Ezra, and Meshullam walking together in the procession alongside civic leaders and priests is a remarkable scene: Ezra — the priest and scribe who had led the second return (Ezra 7–10) and the great Torah reading (Neh 8) — participated in the wall dedication as a walker in procession, not as its focal leader. This reflects the complementary roles of Ezra and Nehemiah: Ezra's domain was Torah instruction and community reform; Nehemiah's domain was civic reconstruction and security. The dedication of the wall was Nehemiah's achievement, and he directs the ceremony accordingly.</p>",
        "34": "<p>The tribal representatives Judah, Benjamin, Shemaiah, and Jeremiah in the procession confirm the community's dual-tribal identity (Judah + Benjamin = the restored Israel). The inclusion of the entire civic-religious leadership in the procession — priests, Levites, tribal heads, scribes — transforms the wall dedication from a civic engineering achievement into a covenant-renewal ceremony. The completed wall was not merely a fortification but a boundary marker of the sacred space within which YHWH's covenant community was constituted.</p>",
        "35": "<p>The priestly trumpeters play instruments specified as belonging to 'David the man of God' (<em>dāwîḏ ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — the same title used in v24. The trumpet (<em>ḥăṣōṣərāh</em>) was a specifically priestly instrument, distinct from the ram's horn (<em>šôfār</em>) used in other contexts (Num 10:1–10). Zechariah son of Jonathan, with his six-generation genealogy tracing back to Asaph, represents the apex of the musical establishment: not only a priest with a trumpet, but a member of the premier musical dynasty authorized by David's prophetic command.</p>",
        "36": "<p>Ezra's role leading this first procession ('Ezra the scribe led the way,' <em>wĕʿezrāʾ hassōfēr liphənêhem</em>) places him at the vanguard of the musicians and priests. The 'instruments of David' (<em>biḵlê-šîr dāwîḏ</em>) were the temple's musical heritage — lyres, harps, and cymbals — associated with the full complement of Levitical praise. The combination of Levitical singers playing Davidic instruments under priestly trumpet accompaniment, with Ezra leading the way, recreates the pattern of Solomon's temple dedication (2 Chr 5:11–13; 7:6) and signals that the wall dedication is a continuation of that founding liturgical moment.</p>",
        "37": "<p>The Fountain Gate and the stairs of the City of David mark key topographical features of the southern Jerusalem ridge. The City of David was the original Jebusite stronghold captured by David (2 Sam 5:7–9) — the procession ascending these stairs was literally ascending to the oldest part of the city. The Water Gate on the east (where the great Torah reading of Neh 8 had taken place) serves as a topographical bookend: the wall procession passes by the place where the Torah was read, connecting the wall's completion to the covenant-renewal that gave it spiritual meaning.</p>",
        "38": "<p>The second procession led by Nehemiah went counterclockwise — northward along the western wall, past the Tower of the Furnaces and the Broad Wall. The Tower of the Furnaces (<em>migdal hattannûrîm</em>) was repaired by Malchijah son of Harim and Hasshub son of Pahath-Moab (Neh 3:11). The Broad Wall is the massive Iron Age wall segment visible today in the Jewish Quarter of the Old City — archaeological excavations have confirmed its existence and its probable relevance to the Nehemianic-era wall system.</p>",
        "39": "<p>The northern route of the second procession passes the Gate of Ephraim, the Old Gate, the Fish Gate, the Tower of Hananel, the Tower of the Hundred, the Sheep Gate, and halts at the Gate of the Guard. This sequence of gates and towers matches the repair sequence of Neh 3:1–15 (northern circuit). The Sheep Gate was where Nehemiah's repair effort began (Neh 3:1), and ending the second procession at the Gate of the Guard nearby creates a structural completion: the narrative of construction began at the Sheep Gate and the dedication procession ends there.</p>",
        "40": "<p>Both thanksgiving choirs converging at the house of God with Nehemiah and half the leaders beside them creates the structural climax of the ceremony. The two processions that divided at the Valley Gate (v31) and proceeded in opposite directions around the entire circumference of the wall now reunite at the temple — the city's sacred center. This convergence structure communicates that the wall encircles and protects the temple, that the city's perimeter exists to serve the center, and that the entire community (not just the priesthood) participates in the consecration of sacred space.</p>",
        "41": "<p>Seven priestly trumpeters are named — Eliakim, Maaseiah, Miniamin, Michaiah, Elioenai, Zechariah, and Hananiah — a number that echoes the seven trumpets of Jericho (Josh 6:4–13) and the Levitical seven in the ark procession (1 Chr 15:24). The trumpet (<em>ḥăṣōṣərāh</em>) in priestly hands was the instrument of sacred announcement — it was blown at the appointed feasts, at the new moon, at the beginning of the year, and in battle (Num 10:1–10). Seven trumpeters at the dedication of Jerusalem's wall signals a new epoch of sacred time for the city.</p>",
        "42": "<p>The singers sang loudly under Jezrahiah their director (<em>mĕqaṣṣîaʿ</em>, H6965 variant — literally 'the one who causes to arise/stand out'). Jezrahiah is otherwise unknown but his title marks a professional musical director role distinct from the priestly trumpeters and the Levitical choral singers. The combination of spontaneous mass rejoicing (v43) and structured professional performance under a director captures the paradox of Israelite worship — simultaneously communal and liturgically ordered, participatory and directed by trained specialists.</p>",
        "43": "<p>The summary — 'God had given them <strong>great joy</strong> (<em>śimḥāh gĕḏôlāh</em>) and the sound of Jerusalem's joy was heard far away' (<em>wattišmaʿ śimḥaṯ yĕrûšālāim mērāḥôq</em>) — deliberately echoes Ezra 3:13, where the sound of weeping at the foundation of the second temple was heard 'far away.' At that earlier moment, the joy of the restoration was mixed with grief for the glory that had been lost. At the wall dedication, the grief is absent: only great joy. The movement from mixed weeping-and-rejoicing (Ezra 3) to pure joy (Neh 12:43) traces the emotional arc of the restoration narrative.</p>",
        "44": "<p>The institutional appointments for temple storerooms (v44) immediately follow the celebration — a characteristic Nehemianic pattern of moving from ceremony to administration. The 'portions required for the priests and Levites' (<em>mənayyôṯ hakkōhănîm wĕhalěwiyyim</em>) by the Law reflect the Levitical tithing system (Num 18:21–28; Deut 14:22–29; Neh 10:37–38) that had broken down in Nehemiah's absence (Neh 13:10–13). The note that 'Judah rejoiced in the priests and Levites who were serving' frames institutional support not as legal compliance but as communal delight in the proper functioning of the covenant community.</p>",
        "45": "<p>The singers' and gatekeepers' maintained 'the requirements of purification as David and his son Solomon had commanded' — the double Davidic-Solomonic authority legitimizes the post-exilic practice as continuity with the united monarchy's temple establishment. The reference to 'Solomon' (the only mention of Solomon in Nehemiah) connects the post-exilic community to the first temple's founding legislation. This Davidic-Solomonic authority structure is the institutional backbone of Chronicles' theology (which Nehemiah/Ezra implicitly shares): the post-exilic community is the legitimate heir of the Davidic covenant's institutional life.</p>",
        "46": "<p>The historical note that 'in the days of David and Asaph, long ago, there had been directors of the singers and songs of praise and thanksgiving' (<em>tĕhillāh wĕhôḏāh lĕʾĕlōhîm</em>) frames the post-exilic musical establishment as a revival of the Davidic original after the disruption of the exile. The phrase 'long ago' (<em>miqqeḏem</em>) acknowledges the temporal distance between David's founding and the post-exilic present — five centuries had passed — while insisting on institutional continuity. Asaph as co-founder alongside David gives the musical institution a dual human-prophetic and royal-administrative authority.</p>",
        "47": "<p>The book of Nehemiah closes this chapter with an institutional summary: 'all Israel provided daily portions for the singers and gatekeepers' in the days of both Zerubbabel (first return) and Nehemiah (second reform), and 'the Levites set apart what was holy for the descendants of Aaron.' The tithing chain — from Israel to Levites to priests — is the Levitical system of Num 18:25–32 functioning as designed. This administrative closure before the crisis of ch13 (where the same system breaks down) makes ch12:47 the high-water mark of the restoration: the community fully organized, the temple fully supported, the wall dedicated, the joy complete.</p>"
    }
}


def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'nehemiah')
    merge_comm(c, NEH1112)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'nehemiah', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in NEH1112.values())
    print(f'nehemiah mkt-context: wrote {count} verses for ch 11–12')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
